  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international guidelines by Basel Committee\n- Initial focus on drug-related financial crimes\n\n2. Major Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) establishment in 1989\n- United Nations Vienna Convention (1988)\n- Patriot Act (2001) expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n3. Key Legislative Developments\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Expanded regulatory oversight\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations covering digital currencies\n- Advanced transaction monitoring systems\n- Cybercrime and cryptocurrency-specific guidelines\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Broader definition of predicate offenses\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- More comprehensive risk-based approaches\n- Focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n\n6. Global Collaboration\n- Multilateral information sharing\n- Consistent international standards\n- Coordinated enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, addressing emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
